                <head>No. 240.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName> to Messrs.
                            <persName type="to">Cushing and McKenney</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">State Department</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1886-04-09">
                            <hi rend="italic">April</hi> 9, 1886</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The question of the right of American vessels engaged in fishing on the high seas
                    to enter Canadian ports for the purpose of shipping crews may possibly involve
                    construction of treaty with Great Britain. I expect to attain such an
                    understanding as will relieve our fishermen from all doubts or risk in the
                    exercise of the ordinary commercial privileges of friendly ports, to which,
                    under existing laws of both countries, I consider their citizens to be mutually
                    entitled free from molestation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>T. E. BAYARD.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
